metadata.name: Landscapes in my mind #23
metadata.description:
In this work I tried to convey the idea of a landscape (many landscapes) with hills, trees, grass, bushes, skies and clouds. As is normal on fxhash I have accomplished all this by writing the code that generates the elements in a scene.
While writing the code to obtain these landscapes I did not try to reproduce landscapes seen in reality or in photography, rather I followed from time to time ideas of landscapes that came to my mind as a sort of lucid dream. I hope I managed to convey this idea of a landscape that is halfway between reality and fantasy.

Lands and Clouds are rendered using a mix of simplex noise and FBM (Fractional Brownian Motion), trees are generated with recursive functions an placed using Poisson Disk Sampling distribution. The distribution density could be homogeneous (land heightmap drive the density) or biased to have more density towards the top, bottom, left or right of the land.


Developed with p5.js using WEBGL renderer.
Rendering is faster with chrome browser.

[1] to render at 1600x1600
[2] to render at 2400x2400
[3] to render at 3200x3200
[s] to save a png at last rendered resolution.


Features:
"LandPalette": 20 colormaps
"TreePalette": 20 colormaps
"Light":  Morning, Evening, Night
"SkyColor": Blue, Azure, Turquoise, Gray, VioletRed
"Haze": True, False
"Rainbow":  True, False
"Grayscale": True, False
"TreeDensity": Homogeneous, Top, Bottom, Left, Right


Created by Andrea Belloni, fxhash: anbello, twitter: @Waterflowing0. Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, see LICENSE.txt for more information.

metadata.name: Lineas #104
metadata.description:
Búscame entre mis letras por que en ellas siempre voy a estar
y en los versos de mis poemas mi corazón escucharás...

Lee cada palabra que encuentres donde quieres buscar
esas que ya conoces y que además te hacen extrañar.
Si te emocionan sueña siempre con algo más, no llores
por que existe un camino donde las letras tienen su punto y final.

El amor es un poema o un milagro terrenal, es la magia
que nos envuelve a los que nos podemos enamorar.
Amar cuesta y cuando se ama duele, se sufre, se llora
por el ser amado, eso es lo que tu alma atesora.

Cada verso que escribo lleva en su contenido un significado,
una promesa, un abrazo entre líneas y un beso de enamorado...

AMOR ENTRE LÍNEAS.
poema de De Lorenzo Román.

-----

Press 'e' to export a 1640 x 2000 pixels PNG

Press 'h' to export a 3280 x 4000 pixels PNG

-----



Artwork by @cristianrohr 2022.

Made with P5js and <3.

metadata.name: Washed Trees Fluor #60
metadata.description:
“Our Love had heard that an immortal language never could die, although silent, it still slept somewhere amongst the birches, lost ever since the day when we went weeping from beneath the angel-guarded gates of Eden.”

In Inner Purple Forest “Washed Trees Fluor”, rainbow bubbles-shaped form sprouts like fungi from a birch log. 

With its disconcerting conjunction of the natural and man-made, this still life recalls the way that nutrients in dead plant material are reclaimed by other living things as part of nature’s cycle of decay and rebirth.

No matter how long or hard we might gaze upon these ghostly images remain the same, they are not allowed to gather too much dust, they do not lose their bloom.

metadata.name: Stack of Shapes #31
metadata.description:
Inspired by sketches I'd draw in my college notebook during class. This piece uses a hand-drawn stroke style to draw a stack of overlapping shapes. Look closely and see that the lines are made of thousands of tiny dots. Iterations vary by color scheme, background color, line thickness, density, and more, with a small chance of using a rainbow color palette.  
  
Press R to re-run the drawing animation; enter to save the image in high quality. Enjoy!

metadata.name: Composition #4 #39
metadata.description:
When I'm working on a problem, I never think about beauty. But when I've finished, if the solution is not beautiful... I know it's wrong.
[Buckminster Fuller]

I tried to hybridize, in a schematic way only, the architectural language of neoplasticism with some characteristics of Islamic architecture. The result seems to me to convey a certain elegance...
As with the other "Composition #" series, you can explore the model interactively in 3D space.

metadata.name: Pixelnetika #12
metadata.description:
-------------------------------------------------

'drop it like it's raw'

-------------------------------------------------
Mouse-click switches between:
- screen scaled image
- The large image - with finer details

right-click: save/copy image

A custom created 'soft' pixel 2D/3D engine 
written in vanilla JavaScript
some more info in the source-code
The work will refresh and restart after some time
-------------------------------------------------

Pixelnetika - magnetic storms - Raw sketch 

-------------------------------------------------
Seen it in the past, whenever a group comes together.
Graffiti scene / Demo scene / Art scene etc. etc. 
New rules start popping up,
you should do this, you should do that..
Can't do this do this, you should not do that.
New rules, that can hinder you. 
If you start conforming/obeying the rules

Like seen people, making lovely works,
'but it should have more variations'
Adding all kinds of extras, 
that only made the work 
less powerful in the end

Or loosing themselves 
in the small details

Making 100 great and lovely sketches,
and finally releasing a work 
that totally did not work or sell at all.

Such a shame.


Well, it does not have enough variations

Variations: != 100 different extras?

For example, look at the Mark's Smoll-skulls or like Casey Reas works,
or like 100 warhol soup-cans, all just a littlebit different

I knew a classic composer, 
that really enjoyed creating works
when he was young.
Became a teacher,
conform within the institution
And lost all the joy he had for composing,
due to pressure and rules 'how things should be done'


Don't post too much

Some people like to work on 1 painting for years
trying to create their own Mona Lisa.

While Vincent van Gogh would paint lightning fast,
sometimes doing 1 painting a day


Break the rules
Make your own rules
set yourself free.
-------------------------------------------------

xxx Amsterdam chillout

For the love of Art, Polar bears, and throwing snowballs ^__^

August 12 2022

metadata.name: ONE WORD (Ed.1) #76
metadata.description:
Inspired by the cut-up technique by William S. Burroughs, which was later used by David Bowie to create some of his song lyrics.

It generates a sequential list of a few hundred words that are placed at random locations on the canvas without overlapping.

Under the hood, a home-built spatial subdivision algorithm is used to look for empty spaces where the next random word might fit.

Originally, the plan was to publish this work with categorized words that somehow fit together into a theme, but after playing around with it, I found that this didn't match the original idea of the cut-up technique.
Also, it was very interesting to see completely arbitrary and unrelated words close together, forming incomplete fragments of a possible sentence. Just use your imagination!

The list of words was created while thinking about the current situation in the world and reading the news. Note, however, that it may happen that some words close to each other form a strange combination.

Press [S] to save in high resolution (long side = 4096 pixels).

Features:

Format - Portrait 40%, Landscape 40%, Square 20%
Canvas - Black 50%, White 50%
Background - Black 50%, White 50%
Post-Effects - None 33%, Light 33%, Strong 33%
Color Drop - Normal 50%, Inverse 50%

made with typescript and pixi.js


2022 // Karuma
